results.notes:
A single fruiting body growing near a trail in mixed deciduous woods with a few scattered conifers in the Stony Lake area.
The general morphology can be inferred from the images.
Cap 5.5 cm wide wide, with a broad central depression, and a tuberculate-short striate margin, medium pink over the disc, pale toward the margin; cuticle pealing 3/4 R. Gills pale cream en masse, subdistant to close, with no forking; short gills very few, some almost reaching the stipe. Stipe 6 cm long, uniformly flushed with a pale pink hue, 1.4 cm wide at the flaring apex and uniformly 1 cm wide below. No discoloration of the surfaces on handling or staining of the exposed flesh noticed. Odor none to faintly fungal. Taste at first slightly bitter, then, after a few seconds, somewhat hot/acrid.
Specimen preserved and will be sequenced.

results.notes:
A single specimen growing in mixed woods (oak, birch, hemlock & pine, maple) in the Stony Lake area. The woods are consistent with where H. subglabripes should be found (more of boreal type seen in New England), though in my opinion this species is rare for NJ. It didn’t smell like old cigarette butts/ash tray, besides H. rubrupunctum is more densely red-punctate and has a darker cap. Specimen preserved.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 22-Nov-23):
The derived full-length nrITS sequence (ONT-nanopore) is 99.6-99.85% similar to 8 GenBank accessions, some of which are called H. subglabripes. Most of the associated vouchers originate from southeastern Canada (4), two are from Oregon (!), one is from NY state (my own obs 294169); the location of the last one is unknown.
It’s remarkable that this species occurs in the West Coast, which can probably be explained by its circumboreal distribution in North America. One of the collections, https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/96965804 by Alan Rockefeller, was apparently made in a coniferous stand.
As stated by me before, it appears that the distribution of H. subglabripes s. str. barely reaches the Mason-Dixon Line from the north. However, it’s possible that it can be found at higher elevations in southeastern Appalachia in mixed woods with hemlock and birch. There is a lookalike species with a more southern distribution, exemplified by obs 244341 from North Carolina; its LSU sequence is only 97.2% (933/960) similar to that of MO294169 referenced above. The three LSU GenBank accessions derived from Indiana collections by Michael Kuo are actually the lookalike of H. subglabripes.

results.notes:
A single specimen growing in mixed deciduous woods in the area of Stony Lake.
The overall macro-morphology can be inferred from the photos. Cap 6 cm wide (footprint), with a broad shallow depression in the disc; cap margin tuberculate and faintly short-striate; the cuticle peeled 1/2 R; cap pigment darker red in the disc, the surface minutely bumpy, and these darker-colored bumps arranged in a way to give the cap a somewhat mottled-zonate appearance. Gills white, but cream en masse, close to subdistant, not forking; lamellulae present, but not abundant, some very short. Stipe 5.5 cm long, 1.2 cm wide at the apex, 1 cm at the narrowest point mid-way and then widening to 1.3 cm at the base, straight, white overall, but flushed with pink in the base and staining tan/brownish when handled. Upon dissection, the cottony stipe context also discolored tan/brownish, the shallow cap context may have stained the same. Taste mild, odor nill, when fresh, but noticeably fishy after drying.
Kibby & Fatto code AIKNQTV, keying out to R. fucosa, which the authors report to be a common member of R. xerampelina group in NJ.
DNA Sequencing Results & Discussion (posted on 27-Apr-22):
A full-length consensus nrITS sequence was obtained from this collection and posted to the observation. In the generated BLASTn-100 hit list, there are 3 matching and 4 near-matching (99.3~99.5% similarity) unnamed North American accessions (from MA, IN and OH), following which % similarity drops to 97.7%; the last reported GenBank hit has a similarity of 96%. The named accessions feature the following Russula species epithets (in alphabetical order): clavipes, faginea, favrei, pasqua, subrubens, viridofusca and xerampalina.
